<!-- 03 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="intro-grid">
      <div class="intro-body">
        <p class="section-number">01, About This Service</p>
        <h2 class="section-title">Microwave repair is one of the few appliance jobs with a genuine safety reason to call a professional.</h2>

        <p>Most appliance repairs are professional-grade because of complexity, tools, or parts availability, not because attempting them yourself poses physical danger. Microwave repair is different. The high-voltage capacitor inside every microwave stores a charge of 2,000 volts or more, and it retains that charge even after the microwave is unplugged. Touching it without properly discharging it first can be fatal. Our technicians discharge the capacitor before any other internal work, it's the first step of every microwave service call, every time.</p>

        <p>The most common microwave call we get across SoCal is "runs but doesn't heat." The cause is almost always the high-voltage diode, a small component that converts the capacitor's charge to the voltage the magnetron needs. When it fails, the magnetron gets no usable power and produces no heat. We carry HV diodes for the brands we see most across SoCal. It's typically a 30-45 minute repair.</p>

        <p>The second common call is over-the-range units, SoCal's apartment and condo stock (from DTLA high-rises to Irvine master-planned community condos to Inland Empire family homes) is full of them, and they have additional components beyond the standard countertop: exhaust fan motor, grease filter, charcoal filter, light assembly mounted over the range. They're also more involved to access for internal repairs since the unit is mounted above a cooktop.</p>

        <div class="tip-safety">
          <div class="tip-label">⚠️ Sparking or Arcing, Stop Using It Now</div>
          <p>If your microwave is producing visible sparks or arcing inside the cavity, stop using it immediately and unplug it. Sparking can indicate a dirty or damaged waveguide cover (sometimes a simple fix), or a failing magnetron (a more significant repair). Operating a sparking microwave can escalate a minor repair into a cavity-wall replacement. Call us first.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <aside class="sticky-cta">
