<!-- 04 HIGH VOLTAGE SAFETY -->
<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Why Microwaves Are Different</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">The one appliance where "look it up on YouTube" can get you killed</h2>
    <p class="lead">We don't say this to generate business. We say it because it's true and most of the content explaining microwave repair online understates the risk significantly.</p>

    <div class="hv-block">
      <div class="hv-label">⚡ High Voltage Hazard</div>
      <h3>2,000+ volts. Stored in the capacitor. Still there after you unplug it.</h3>
      <p>A microwave's high-voltage capacitor is charged to 2,100 volts or more during operation. Unlike most appliances where unplugging the unit removes all electrical hazard, a microwave capacitor holds its charge for hours or days after disconnection. The capacitor is physically located near the magnetron and high-voltage transformer, areas a technician must access to diagnose the most common microwave failures.</p>
      <p>The proper procedure is to discharge the capacitor with an insulated resistor before any other internal work. This takes about 30 seconds if you know what you're doing and have the right tool. Without it, any contact with the capacitor terminals or the wiring connected to them can deliver a lethal shock. Our technicians do this as the first step, every time, without exception.</p>

      <div class="hv-points">
        <div class="hv-point">
          <strong>2,100V stored charge</strong>
          <span>Standard residential microwave capacitor voltage, several times what causes cardiac arrest</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hv-point">
          <strong>Persists after unplugging</strong>
          <span>Capacitor holds charge for hours with no power, unplugging is not sufficient protection</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hv-point">
          <strong>Near common failure points</strong>
          <span>Capacitor, diode, and magnetron are all co-located, you must pass near it to reach them</span>
        </div>
        <div class="hv-point">
          <strong>Discharge procedure required</strong>
          <span>Requires an insulated resistor and correct technique, not a screwdriver across the terminals</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 MICROWAVE TYPES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">03, Microwave Types We Service</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Every configuration in SoCal homes</h2>

    <div class="type-grid">
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Countertop</div>
        <h3>Countertop Microwaves</h3>
        <p>The most common type. Easiest to access for repair. Key consideration: for basic models under $150, compare repair cost against replacement cost before proceeding. We give you this assessment upfront.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Over-the-Range</div>
        <h3>Over-the-Range (OTR) Microwaves</h3>
        <p>Mounted above the cooktop. Includes exhaust fan, grease filter, charcoal filter, and cooktop lighting in addition to standard microwave components. More involved to access, unit often needs partial unm ounting to reach internal parts.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Built-In</div>
        <h3>Built-In &amp; Drawer Microwaves</h3>
        <p>Integrated into cabinetry, Wolf, Miele, Thermador, Monogram. Higher-end installations with trim kits and cabinetry-matching panels. Removal and reinstallation requires care with the surrounding cabinetry. Almost always worth repairing given replacement + installation cost.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="type-card">
        <div class="type-badge">Convection</div>
        <h3>Convection Microwaves</h3>
        <p>Combination microwave and convection oven, common in smaller SoCal kitchens where counter space is limited (DTLA condos, Westside apartments, OC coastal cottages, Conejo Valley townhomes). Additional components: convection fan, heating element. Both systems can fail independently.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 06 PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04, Common Problems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians fix most often</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Microwave Runs But No Heat</h3>
        <p>High-voltage diode failure is the most common cause, by a significant margin. The diode converts AC power to the DC voltage the magnetron needs. When it fails, the magnetron gets no usable power. The microwave appears to run normally (light, turntable, timer) but produces no heat. We carry HV diodes for the major brands.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Sparking or Arcing Inside</h3>
        <p>Could be a coated or damaged waveguide cover (the flat panel covering the magnetron opening inside the cavity, food residue can carbonize and arc). Could also indicate a failing magnetron. Stop using the unit and call us. Operating a sparking microwave can damage the cavity walls and escalate a minor repair significantly.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Won't Turn On</h3>
        <p>Door switches are the first thing to check, microwaves have two or three interlock switches that must all register "closed" for the unit to operate. A failed line fuse (often blown by a power surge) or a thermal fuse that's tripped from overheating are also common causes. We carry door switches and fuses for the major brands.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Door Won't Open or Latch</h3>
        <p>The door latch assembly and door hooks are mechanical parts that wear with use. A broken door hook or latch spring is common on units that see heavy daily use. On some models the door release button itself fails. These are purely mechanical repairs, no high-voltage involvement, and usually quick fixes.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Turntable Not Spinning</h3>
        <p>The turntable motor sits under the glass plate and rotates it during operation. When it fails, the plate stays stationary and food heats unevenly. Also check: whether the turntable coupler (the plastic drive piece) has cracked or stripped. Motor or coupler replacement is one of the simpler microwave repairs.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Touchpad / Buttons Not Responding</h3>
        <p>A failed membrane touchpad is the most common cause, the conductive membrane behind the buttons degrades over time. Sometimes just the ribbon connector between the touchpad and the control board has come loose. A failed control board is less common but possible. We test the touchpad and connector before recommending a board replacement.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Microwave Overheating / Shuts Off</h3>
        <p>A thermal fuse or thermal protector that's tripping due to actual overheating, often caused by a blocked vent or a failed cooling fan, or one that's failed and trips prematurely. We check the vent and fan function before replacing the thermal component, because the root cause matters.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Loud Noise During Operation</h3>
        <p>A grinding or humming sound usually indicates the turntable motor is failing or the turntable ring guide has broken. A buzzing from the transformer area can indicate a high-voltage issue. Rattling from the exhaust area on an OTR unit usually means a loose grease filter or a worn fan bearing.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

