    <h2 class="section-title">The honest guide, because microwave economics vary a lot by type</h2>
    <p class="lead">A microwave repair decision depends entirely on what type of unit you have. The economics are very different between a basic countertop and a built-in drawer microwave.</p>

    <div class="rvr-grid">
      <div class="rvr-card repair-yes">
        <div class="rvr-badge badge-yes">✓ Usually Worth Repairing</div>
        <h3>These microwaves are almost always worth fixing</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list yes">
          <li>Over-the-range units, replacement requires professional installation ($200–$400)</li>
          <li>Built-in / drawer units, cabinetry work needed for replacement</li>
          <li>Wolf, Thermador, Miele, Monogram built-ins, units cost $800–$3,000+</li>
          <li>Convection combo units, replacement cost is high</li>
          <li>Any microwave with a simple mechanical failure (door, turntable, fuse)</li>
          <li>Any unit under 5 years old, magnetron failures are rare this early</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="rvr-card repair-no">
        <div class="rvr-badge badge-no">✗ Often Not Worth Repairing</div>
        <h3>When replacement usually makes more sense</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list no">
          <li>Countertop units under $150, repair cost often exceeds replacement</li>
          <li>Any unit over 10 years old with magnetron failure</li>
          <li>Units with severe cavity damage from arcing</li>
          <li>Basic models where multiple components have failed</li>
          <li>Units where repair cost exceeds 75% of replacement cost</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
