<!-- 09 RECENT REPAIRS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">07, Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Newport Beach (Orange County) · LG Over-the-Range LMV2031ST</div>
        <h3>"Runs but absolutely no heat, timer counts down, nothing happens"</h3>
        <p>High-voltage diode failure, the most common microwave repair we do. The unit was running normally in every way that didn't require heat: light, turntable, timer, control panel. The diode had failed open, so the magnetron received no DC voltage. Standard HV diode failure presentation on an LG OTR that had been in service for 6 years.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Discharged HV capacitor per safety protocol. Tested diode, open circuit confirmed. Replaced HV diode with OEM LG part. Verified heating with a cup of water before closing up, 2 minutes to boiling confirmed. 35-minute total repair. Customer had been using the cooktop range hood function during the week without microwave, that continued to work normally throughout.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Pasadena (LA County) · GE Profile Built-In JVM7195SKSS</div>
        <h3>"Sparking inside every time we use it, smells burnt"</h3>
        <p>Damaged waveguide cover. The plastic cover over the magnetron opening inside the cavity had a carbonized area where food residue had arced repeatedly over time, making the damage progressively worse. Left another week of use, this could have damaged the cavity wall itself, which is a much more expensive repair or a unit replacement. Caught early, it was a $35 part.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced waveguide cover with OEM GE part, cleaned the cavity walls thoroughly (some carbon residue on the opposite wall from the arcing), verified no pitting or damage to the cavity paint. Tested for 5 minutes with no sparking. Advised customer on the importance of keeping the waveguide cover clean and covering food to prevent recurrence.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Thousand Oaks (Ventura County) · Samsung ME21R706BAT OTR</div>
        <h3>"Three buttons on the touchpad stopped working, can't set time"</h3>
        <p>Membrane touchpad failure, three adjacent buttons (the 4, 5, 6 number keys) had failed simultaneously, which usually indicates a damaged section of the membrane rather than individual switch failures. Common on units that see heavy use or where cleaning solution has gotten behind the panel. The control board itself was functional.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Replaced touchpad membrane assembly with OEM Samsung part. All buttons verified functional before closing. Noted to customer that the ribbon cable connector had a small amount of moisture residue, cleaned and secured. 40-minute repair including teardown and reassembly of the control panel.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Beverly Hills (LA County) · Wolf MDD30TE Drawer Microwave</div>
        <h3>"Door won't latch, spring broke and now the drawer won't stay closed"</h3>
        <p>Failed door latch spring on a Wolf drawer microwave, drawer microwaves have a different latch mechanism than standard door units, using a spring-loaded catch that engages when the drawer closes. The spring had fatigued and broken. Wolf built-in units almost always make financial sense to repair given replacement + cabinetry reinstallation cost.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Sourced OEM Wolf latch spring assembly (2-day lead time from authorized distributor). Replaced spring, tested drawer closure and interlock switch engagement through 10 cycles. Microwave operating normally. Customer noted the repair cost was roughly 8% of what a replacement unit + reinstallation would have cost.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

