<!-- 11 FAQ -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">09, Frequently Asked Questions</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Microwave repair, what people ask us</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How much does microwave repair cost?</h3>
        <p>Our diagnostic fee is $89, applied toward the repair once you approve the work. Most microwave repairs run between $100 and $250. A door switch, HV diode, turntable motor, or touchpad replacement is toward the lower end. Magnetron replacement is the higher end, we give you an honest repair vs. replace assessment before recommending it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Which areas of Southern California do you cover?</h3>
        <p>All five counties: Los Angeles, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside. We dispatch from 8 service territories so the technician on your call is coming from the closest one. Same-day is our standard.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Why is microwave repair dangerous to attempt yourself?</h3>
        <p>Microwaves contain a high-voltage capacitor that stores 2,000+ volts and retains that charge even after unplugging. Touching it without properly discharging it first can be fatal. Our technicians discharge the capacitor as the first step before any internal work, every time, without exception.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My microwave is sparking or arcing inside, is it safe to use?</h3>
        <p>No. Stop using it and unplug it. Sparking can indicate a dirty or damaged waveguide cover (sometimes simple to fix) or a failing magnetron (more serious). Operating a sparking microwave can damage the cavity walls and turn a minor repair into a major one, or a replacement.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My microwave runs but doesn't heat, what's usually wrong?</h3>
        <p>High-voltage diode failure, by far the most common cause. The diode converts power for the magnetron, and when it fails the microwave appears to run normally (light, turntable, timer) but produces no heat. We carry HV diodes for the major brands. Usually a 30–45 minute repair once diagnosed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>When does it make sense to repair vs replace a microwave?</h3>
        <p>It depends on the type. A basic countertop under $150 is often not worth repairing. An over-the-range or built-in unit almost always is, replacement requires professional installation adding $200–$500. Premium built-ins (Wolf, Miele, Thermador) are almost always worth repairing given the unit cost. We give you this assessment during the diagnostic.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Do you repair over-the-range and built-in microwaves?</h3>
        <p>Yes. OTR and built-in units are more involved than countertop units, partial dismounting is often required to access internal components. We work on these regularly and come prepared with mounting knowledge for GE, KitchenAid, Samsung, LG, Whirlpool, Bosch, and Wolf.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What does the 90-day warranty cover on microwave repairs?</h3>
        <p>Every microwave repair we complete carries a 90-day warranty on both parts and labor. If the same issue returns within that window, we come back at no charge. That's in writing before we leave.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

